##* {{quote-book|en|author=J[ohn] T. Lucker|author2=A. O. Foster|chapter=Adult Tapeworms|title=Parasites and Parasitic Diseases of Sheep|series=Farmers’ Bulletin|seriesvolume=no. 1330|location=Washington, D.C.|publisher={{w|United States Department of Agriculture}}|month=May|year=1957|page=38|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=nrteJmgpba0C&pg=PA38|oclc=15715327|passage=The eggs [of a lancet fluke (''[[Dicrocoelium dendriticum]]'')] that pass out with the manure of an infested sheep do not hatch in the open. When eaten by the snail, they hatch and finally give rise to larvae that pass out of the snail's body in gelatinous "'''slime'''[-]'''balls'''."}}
##* {{quote-book|en|author=J[ames] D[esmond] Smyth|chapter=Digenea: Bucephalidae, Fasciolidae, Opisthorchiidae, Dicrocoeliidae|title=Introduction to Animal Parasitology|series=Biological Science Texts|edition=2nd|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=[[w:Wiley (publisher)|John Wiley & Sons]]|year=1976|page=181|column=2|isbn=978-0-470-98921-0|edition2=3rd|location2=Cambridge, Cambridgeshire; New York, N.Y.|publisher2={{w|Cambridge University Press}}|year2=1994|page2=215|pageurl2=https://books.google.com/books?id=j1TD9FiEY-sC&pg=PA215|column2=2|isbn2=978-0-521-41770-9|passage=The cercariae contain massive glands, formerly considered to be penetration glands, but now believed to produce the slime responsible for the formation of these balls. It is likely that the slime produced by the snail itself may contribute, at least partly, to the formation of a '''slimeball'''.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|author=A. M. Marty|author2=E. M. Andersen|chapter=Helminthology|editors=Wilhelm Doerr, Gerhard Seifert, and Erwin Uehlinger|title=Tropical Pathology|series=Spezielle pathologische Anatomie, ein Lehr- und Nachschlagewerk [Special Pathological Anatomy: A Teaching and Reference Work]|seriesvolume=8|edition=2nd|location=Berlin; Heidelberg|publisher=[[w:Springer Science+Business Media|Springer-Verlag]]|year=1995|page=827|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ty248lJd1HIC&pg=PA827|isbn=978-3-540-57673-0|passage=These flukes have three hosts. [...] As the infected snail crawls along it leaves '''slime balls''' containing cercaria on grass. An ant, ''Formica fusa'', the arthropod host for ''D. dendriticum'' in the United States, is infected when it ingests the '''slime balls'''. Mammals are infected by consuming ants containing encysted metacercaria.}}
